{{infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|name=江原神社|location=朝鮮江原道春川郡春川邑|deity=天照大神<br/>明治天皇<br/>国魂大神<br/>素戔嗚尊|Rank=国幣小社|established=[[1918]]（大正7th year ）|festival=10月15日}}'''Kogen-jinja''' Shrine was a shrine located in Chuncheon-gun, Gangwon-do, Korea

The enshrined deities were [[Amaterasu|Amaterasu Omikami]], [[Emperor Meiji]], [[Kunitama Omikami]], and [[Susanoo|Susanoo no Mikoto]]. Sosawo-son was added to Mt. Gozu in Chuncheon, including Gisangbong Peak, as it was one of the identified places of Soshimori of Silla.

It was associated with imperialism and State Shinto rather than local belief in Shintoism.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Nakajima|first=Michio|date=2010|title=Shinto Deities that Crossed the Sea: Japan's "Overseas Shrines," 1868 to 1945|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/27822898|journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies|volume=37|issue=1|pages=21–46|issn=0304-1042|jstor=27822898}}</ref>{{Rp|30}}

  During that time, the government forced people to visit shrines instead of visiting them voluntarily.<ref name=":02">{{Cite journal|last=Nakajima|first=Michio|date=2010|title=Shinto Deities that Crossed the Sea: Japan's "Overseas Shrines," 1868 to 1945|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/27822898|journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies|volume=37|issue=1|pages=21–46|issn=0304-1042|jstor=27822898}}</ref>{{Rp|38}}

Because of Japan's loss in World War II, the shrine was abolished on November 17, 1945.<ref>内務省告示第264号 官報第5660号（昭和20th year 11月22日） 1頁</ref>

